<font color="#FF0000">RACISM</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 29  9:01:57 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
 I have not seen the &quot;real&quot; monument.  I have seen the &quot;moving wall&quot;.  Even in miniature this monument affected me the way only one other ever has.  When I was six I saw the Lincoln Memorial for the first time.  At six years of age I felt awestruck for the first time.  I feel that way about the Wall and my memory of it.  I am old enough that I am sure that I know some of the names on that wall and I cry when I think of it and the sorrow it represents.  <br><br>
I was appalled when the controversy arose over Maya Lin's design being chosen.  I am still.  We are doomed to struggle until we learn, and we do not seem to be learning too quickly, that we are all the same and we must allow each other to be different.  <br><br>
Bright Blessings in the coming holiday season.  Please take the time to reflect that the names on the wall represent people, and only those who knew the individuals can tell the color of their skin.
<p><code>-- cnoyes@voyager.net  (C.E. Noyes) </code><p>


